3 - marital: marital status (categorical: 'divorced','married','single','unknown'; note: 'divorced' means divorced or widowed)¶
4 - education: (categorical: primary, secondary, tertiary and unknown)¶
5 - default: has credit in default? (categorical: 'no','yes','unknown')¶
6 - housing: has housing loan? (categorical: 'no','yes','unknown')¶
7 - loan: has personal loan? (categorical: 'no','yes','unknown')¶
8 - balance: Balance of the individual.¶

Data Related to the last contact of the current campaign:¶

9 - contact: contact communication type (categorical: 'cellular','telephone')¶
10 - month: last contact month of year (categorical: 'jan', 'feb', 'mar', ..., 'nov', 'dec')¶
11 - day: last contact day of the week (categorical: 'mon','tue','wed','thu','fri')¶
12 - duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric). Important note: this attribute highly affects the output target (e.g., if duration=0 then y='no'). Yet, the duration is not known before a call is performed. Also, after the end of the call y is obviously known. Thus, this input should only be included for benchmark purposes and should be discarded if the intention is to have a realistic predictive model.¶

Other independent attributes:¶

13 - campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)¶
14 - pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric; 999 means client was not previously contacted)¶
15 - previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric)¶
16 - poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical: 'unknown', 'failure','other','success')¶

## function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Precision is the proportion of correct predictions of that class that are true. So the decision tree is 93% correct in predicting a No to Term deposit subscription.¶

Its precision in correctly predicting a 'Yes' to subscribing the Term deposit is 61.1% which is fairly good but this needs to be improved to ensure customers who have higher probsbility of accepting the subscription are not missed out.¶

Recall is the proportion of the true positives that are identified correctly. This means that this decision tree model is correctly identifying 97% of the class 0s, but only 39.5% of the class 1s. Thus here too the model is strong in identifying which customers would NOT go ahead with subscription but the model does a relatively poorer job in correctily identifying the customers who are very likely to subscribe the Term deposit. As the case in precision thie decision tree model needs to be tuned to increase its recall to help increase the prediction which would help capture a bigger base of Term deposit customers¶

F1-Score is a kind of average of precision and recall; In statistical analysis of binary classification, the F1 score (also F-score or F-measure) is a measure of a test's accuracy. it's a scale to provide an overall unified figure of the model's performance, It's calculated via the formula 2 x ((precision x recall) / (precision + recall)). As shown for presion and recall the model's F1-Score shows the model's ability in correctly predicting class 1 i.e. Yes and lower accuracy in predicting¶

The AUC under ROC curve is 0.87 indicating a fairly accurate model. While Precision, Recall and F1 scores are relatively less for class 1 i.e. for Yes, a higher ROC indicates the probability that the model ranks a random positive example more highly than a random negative example.¶

Thus combining all four factors we can say the model is good in preciing rhe negative outcome i.e. TN but it can be improved in better predicting TP.¶

Performance Metrics¶
  • Precision: Fraction of actuals per label that were correctly classified by the model
  • Recall: Fraction of predictions that were correctly classified by the model
  • F1-score: Weighted harmonic mean of the precision and recall. F1-score: 2 (precision recall) / (precision + recall)
  • Support: Number of occurrences of each class in y_test
  • Accuracy: Fraction of all observations that were correctly classified by the model
  • Macro avg: Calculate metrics for each label, and find their unweighted mean. This does not take label imbalance into account
  • Micro/weighted avg: Calculate metrics globally by counting the total true positives, false negatives and false positives
  • AUC Score: Given a random observation from the dataset that belongs to a class, and a random observation that doesn't belong to a class, the AUC is the perecentage of time that our model will classify which is which correctly
